### useState

`useState` is the most fundamental React hook. It adds state to functional components, allowing them to remember values across renders.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useState } from 'react';

const [state, setState] = useState(initialValue);
```

### Multiple State Variables

```jsx
const [name, setName] = useState('');
const [age, setAge] = useState(0);
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
```

### Lazy Initialization

Pass a function to compute the initial state only once:

```jsx
const [data, setData] = useState(() => {
  return expensiveComputation();
});
```

### State Update Patterns

| Pattern | Code | Use Case |
|---------|------|----------|
| Direct | `setCount(5)` | Setting to a specific value |
| Functional | `setCount(c => c + 1)` | Based on previous state |
| Object spread | `setUser(u => ({...u, name}))` | Merging object state |
| Array spread | `setItems(i => [...i, newItem])` | Adding to array |

### State Batching

React batches state updates for performance. Multiple `setState` calls in an event handler trigger a single re-render.

```jsx
function handleClick() {
  setCount(c => c + 1);
  setFlag(f => !f);
  // Single re-render at the end
}
```

> **Key Point:** State updates are asynchronous. If you need the latest state immediately, use useEffect or calculate the value from the updater function.

codeExample:
import { useState } from 'react';

function ShoppingCart() {
  const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
  const [total, setTotal] = useState(0);

  const addItem = (item) => {
    setItems(prev => [...prev, item]);
    setTotal(prev => prev + item.price);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Items: {items.length}</p>
      <p>Total: ${total.toFixed(2)}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
